Using this as a guide: https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/20/what-next-for-boris-johnson-brexit-deal-withdrawal-bill-vote. I assume after the PM tries to pass a meaningful vote, the Speaker, Mr. Bercow, will block such a motion, but also that, whether the govternment's motion is allowed or blocked, some form of Letwin will ensure that there is a high likelihood of an extension to Article 50. There are sound legal reasons for the EU extending article 50: Gina Miller in a legal paper pointed out – “the wording of article 50(3) presupposes that the European council take the decisive lead with the consent of the withdrawing member state”. Secondly, 'the EU has a legal duty to all its member states to ensure that any such withdrawal is not damaging to what article 13(1) of the treaty on European Union calls the “consistency, effectiveness and continuity of its policies and actions”, or to the principle spelled out in article 13(2): “Pursuant to the principle of sincere cooperation the EU and the member states shall, in full mutual respect, assist each other in carrying out the tasks which flow from the treaties.”' (https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/mar/03/gina-miller-eu-delay-brexit-no-deal). The economic consequences of a hard Brexit will be massive. Consequently, I believe that the EU will grant, if needed, an extension to article 50. As I write, Mr. Bercow is speaking (https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2019/oct/21/brexit-johnson-to-push-for-deal-as-labour-woos-rebel-tories-eu-extension-live-news) and has just blocked the government's motion. Given Labour's concerns over withdrawal agreement Mr. Johnson has negotiated, and the concerns of the DUP and others, and the vast chasm between the opposition and the government on matters related to a custom's union and a confirmatory referendum, the EU will likely have to grant an extension. In the least, there is so little time left to get on with it. There is no majority for a second referendum as things stand. Mr. Johnson cannot achieve Brexit without an election, but, as recent polling indicates, he is unlikely to win an election without Brexit (https://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/uknews/boris-johnson-will-only-win-a-general-election-if-brexit-is-delivered-by-31-october-poll-suggests/ar-AAICVfG), so his endgame is Brexit, deal or no deal. Yet, a "People v Parliament" election (https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/boris-johnson-lays-ground-for-people-v-politicians-general-election-tf9v7nkg5) could win him a majority, in my mind, and he may gamble that he has done enough to hurt the Brexit Party and his messaging and the manner in which he asked for an extension of article 50, suggest that that is his thinking (https://www.politico.com/news/2019/10/18/boris-johnson-charms-parliament-brexit-election-050700) and he will call for a general election to Get Brexit Done.

This comment is not a forecast. What I think should happen with this badly conceived Brexit process it that a WA should be aproved, then a fully defined Future Trading Relationship (FTR) should be agreed. Then a public vote of on the WA and the FTR. Then (if the public agreed) an implementation period started. This is more or less what the sequence that was supposed be. All I have added is the Public Vote and that what was called the Future Framework is worked up into a legal text. The reason for adding the Public Vote is that the 2016 referendum was a vote to change the UK relationship to the EU, without clarity on what relationship the public wanted. The reason for making the FTR a legal document is that without legal certainty the public can't be sure where the UK relationship will finish up. (With BJ as PM many are suspicious that the FTA will not be agreed because many Conservative Breiteers prefer what the Brexit Party wants, and the BJ deal is just a means of getting there.) The reason for starting the implementation period after both the WA and FTR become law, is that until the final destination has being agreed its not possible to start implementing it.

The DUP has said this morning they will not vote for this WA. Maybe they will change their minds, but if the WA is as described in the media it would create a big problem for the DUP. It might be thought that as the DUP is a party in favour of Brexit it would be keen to agree BJ's deal, but that ignores what the point of the DUP is. Without going back into Irish history its necessary to understand what the DUP's raison d'etre is. Its underlying purpose was to stop what their supporters saw as the risk of Irish Protestants being overwhelmed by Irish Catholics. The Protestants saw themselves as British, the Catholics were seen as Irish Popests. Before the 1960s the NI Protestants controlled the NI government, police and business, but the 1960s saw the rise of protest movements in many countries where communities who felt they were being denied civil rights started agitating for their civil rights. When you increase the civil rights of one group the previously dominant group if usually not happy. So the DUP raison d'etre is to stop NI becoming like Ireland. The Good Friday Agreement recognized this and gave both the Protestants and Catholics vetos on changes. As far as I can understand the issue with the BJ WA is what exactly "a change" is. Most people in NI would see "a change" as being something that alters the current arrangement between NI and Ireland. The DUP sees "a change" as something that alters the current arrangement between NI and GB. Logically if GB itself changes (by not being in the EU and having some as yet unknown trading relationship) but NI remains aligned with Ireland and the EU, then a future change in NI to remove this alignment with the EU, this change ought to be agreed by both communities. As the majority of voters in NI were not in favour of Brexit, it seems unlikely that there would be cross community consensus for NI to change what (I assume) is in the BJ WA. So the DUP would see NI's economy becoming more integrated with Ireland's and less like GB's. The inconvenience of the paper work and duties paid and maybe refunded required for NI/GB trade compared to frictionless trade between NI and Ireland (and the EU) would be certain to gradually mean NI become more like Ireland (and probable eventually lead to a united Ireland. So for the DUP the long term affect of voting for BJ's WA could make the party irrelevant.

As the public and most MPs (and possibly no EU 27 Governments) have not yet seen a clear outline of what is being negotiated, let alone seen a legal text and the Benn Act sets a deadline of 19th Oct before the PM has to ask for an Extention to A50 it seems very likely that A50 would have to be extended before the UK can Leave the EU with a Deal in Place. The Benn Act requires not just that the UK agrees in principal to a WA, but that "a Deal" has been voted thru the UK Parliament. As the deal between Mrs May and EU ran to over 600 pages, (and was very difficult to read because lots of sections required that the reader read other legal documents in order to understand variations to them that the WA would entail). I can't see MPs voting on such an important document that they (or their legal advisors) have not had time to read, and that they have not had time to discuss with their constituents, by 19th Oct. Its possible that if BJ requests an Extension to A50 as required by the Benn Act, that the EU could delay replying to the request until they have a clear idea what the UK would use the extension for. For example they might delay replying in order to see if the UK Parliament will vote for it before the 31st Oct. If the extension had been requested but the UK Parliament then voted thru a WA, then the Extension would (probably) not happen.
I find it very difficult to believe that the new deal they are discussing will pass the EU27 nor parliament, nevertheless, there seems a chance.

Following the expulsion of 21 MPs from the Conservative Party, the government no longer has the numbers even in theory to get a deal through Parliament. Paradoxically, this has weakened the position of the DUP, which no longer holds the balance of power. Boris Johnson's attempts to negotiate a new deal have not been received warmly in Brussels, which has no confidence that any deal can now make it through Parliament. Meanwhile, the opposition parties are determined to keep the Conservatives in government until November, having passed a law requiring the government to seek a Brexit extension. This means that Johnson's options are likely to be a) no-deal Brexit (now illegal); b) seek an extension (political suicide in the forthcoming election); or c) resignation (a humiliating end to his political career). I suspect that, as a natural risk-taker, he may well opt for a no-deal Brexit, at which point it will be up to the Conservative Parliamentary Party to decide quickly whether to demand his resignation in the knowledge that it would likely destroy their electoral prospects, or be complicit in breaking the law. The slightly higher probability I have given to no-deal Brexit reflects the fact that those MPs most likely to oppose Johnson are no longer members of his party.

Currently, to distract the public from Mr. Corbyn's Salford pronouncement that a non-confidence motion may happen tomorrow, Mr. Johnson muses about calling an election. Very clever: Corbyn is less likely to act this week if it may be seen as on Johnson's prerogative. It's the British version of flip-flop tweeting. Maintaining the absence of rational thought appears to be key strategy: gain fame for messing your hair and making inane noises when cornered on TV, or throw out packages of paper towel at a hurricane disaster relief meeting, but avoid getting serious at all costs. And, if an election is called before September 12th, then Mr. Johnson will do all in his power to set the date without consulting the EU first. Time is more pressing than some of players seem to think. If the Labour Party's preferred option is to try to get a date set for a General Election their window of opportunity is very small. Presumably Labour would demand a vote of confidence in whoever is the next PM. They can't do that before 4th Sep, (I assume a vote of No Confidence in Mrs May would be pointless because she has already said she is resigning) because the process for forcing a General election requires two No Confidence votes two weeks apart and Parliament will be closed from 25 July to 3 Sept (Mrs May is expected to remain PM until 23 July). In September Parliament will only be in session between 4 Sep and 12 Sep, it them closes for the Party Conferences and reopens on 7 Oct (I think). If the first Confidence vote had already been lost by then the second vote could take place in that week, and then a General Election could be called it is assumed (no one seems to have tested the assumption) that a General Election requires a notice period of at least 6 weeks. So it appears virtually impossible for a General Election to take place before 31st Oct. In theory a PM who had just lost two No Confidence Votes could ask the EU to extend A50 to allow a General Election to be held after 31 Oct, but clearly a Conservative PM who had just lost Parliaments Confidence but had the option of extending A50 or allowing a No Deal Brexit to happen would be under a lot of pressure to let No Deal happen. Obviously if its already too late to have a General Election before 31 Oct, calling for a vote of No Confidence would not be a useful tactic to prevent a No Deal Brexit happening on 31 Oct. It would probably be easier for a Parliament that wanted to block a No Deal Brexit to pass legislation demanding the PM ask for an A50 extension than try to force a General Election.

In case there is any doubt that forecasting this question is difficult I offer today's example; On the BBC Politics Live today, a Conservative MP representing Boris Johnson gets into an argument as to whether Johnson plans to renegotiate the Brexit WA before November. The MP says Johnson has assured him that the WA will not be renegotiated, it will merely have a few words added to the Backstop section, which the MP considered too small a change to count as renegotiation. While the studio guests argue if this is or is not renegotiation, a tweet is sent by Steve Baker who is also a Johnson for PM supporter to say that he has been promised, by Johnson, several other changes to the WA in particular that the European Court of Justice will not have any role during the 2 year implementation period. It seems likely that Johnson is promising different things to each MP that will vote for him to be PM. So now travel forward a few weeks and Johnson is PM and he goes to the EU (and lets assume they agree to discuss the WA) does he say "I don't need to renegotiate the WA I just need a one line change to the Backstop"? My guess is that either the EU just say "No" or they say "if we agree this one line change can you guarantee you can get it thru Parliament?" If Johnson says "yes" and the EU agree to the change, but then Baker and ERG (Conservatives) refuse to vote for it because they demand more changes, the EU wil tell Johnson to take a hike. If Johnson says "No" the EU will certainly tell Johnson to take a hike. As the EU is as capable as I am of watching BBC TV they already know that Johnson is telling different supporters different things and that what ever he asked for from the EU will be rejected by at least some Conservative MPs (and almost all non-Conservative MPs) so nothing short of full renegotiation of WA with nothing hidden so no last minute surprises arise, will produce a WA that Parliament will vote thru, and that WA would need cross party support not rely on just the Conservative Party MPs and DUP MPs. It would only take a handful of Conservatives to block any version of a WA as too hard or too soft (especially likely with Johnson as PM). There is not time to do a complete renegotiation of the WA before November even if the EU wanted to. To pretend otherwise is setting things up for a certain failure. So as far as I am concerned Johnson might as well be written off now because his statement that agreeing the WA is feasible before November can only happen if he has a way of getting Parliament to vote for Mrs Mays's WA.

I am lowering extension chances on the following argument: it now seems to me (contrary to arguments by e.g. @nigster) that an extension does not have to happen before a date for a referendum or GE is set. For, even if an extension is not granted in time for the GE or referendum, the UK can always revoke A50 and the EU knows that. Overall, my assumption is that the extension is not a binding constraint but a procedural one, and as such it will fall in line when a political agreement is reached. As with other topics of international law, politics sometimes (often?) comes before norms and procedures.

May's government and the Labour Party could reach a Brexit agreement. For over a month, May's Conservative-led government and Labour, the main opposition party, have been discussing a Brexit agreement that both sides could support in Parliament. I am approaching this question by starting with what most MPs don't want to happen. There are probably less than 10% of MPs who would countenance Leaving the EU with No Deal. If circumstances arose that made No Deal the default I believe MPs would block it by forcing the Government to Revoke A50. MPs would only Revoke A50 if the choice was that or No Deal. There would be a huge complaint from 35% or so of the pubic if A50 was revoked without some very good reason.

The next Prime Minister is likely to be a Brexiteer, so the prospect of another EU referendum is also low. The EU has been adamant that the Withdrawal Agreement will not be renegotiated, and it would be difficult for a Conservative Party leadership contender to advocate leaving with the unpopular deal secured by Theresa May. Hard Brexit against the wishes of the Commons would provoke a constitutional crisis, leaving a further extension as by far the most likely outcome.
